The paper deals with set reconciliation problems in a metric space, which involves data structures and algorithms for efficient processing of sets. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also utilizes locality sensitive hashing, which is a technique commonly used in information theory (cs.IT) and database systems (cs.DB) for similarity search and indexing. The paper deals with geometric settings, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves analyzing the performance of algorithms, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category.
